[[File:American Military Engineers emblem.jpg|250px|thumb|right|American Military Engineers]] The '''Goethals Medal''' is a national award given annually by the [[Society of American Military Engineers]] (SAME) to a [[Professional Engineer|registered engineer]] who is also a member of SAME prior to nomination. The nominated engineer must have made ''eminent and notable contributions in engineering, design, or construction in the past five years.''
The award is named in honor of General [[George Washington Goethals]], a [[civil engineer]] and [[United States Army]] [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] best known for his work as [[Chief engineer]] on the [[Panama Canal]] and his service in [[WWI]] as Acting [[Quartermaster General of the United States Army|Quartermaster General]].<ref>Scientific and Technical Societies of the United States and Canada. (1961) - Canada, p355.</ref><ref name=CMH>{{cite book| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/books/panama/panamacanal/| title=The Panama Canal:An Army's Enterprise| publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]]| year=2009| id=CMH Pub 70-115-1| pages=13–15}}</ref><ref>McCullough, David (1977), The Path Between the Seas: The Creation of the Panama Canal, 1870–1914, New York: Simon & Schuster. pp. 505-508. {{ISBN|0-671-24409-4}}</ref>
